Chapter 10 Canonical Correlation Analysis (CCA)¶

Usually, the correlation is to quantify the linear association bewtween two quantiative variables. Canonical correlation analysis (CCA) is to identify and quantify the associations within two sets of multivariate quantitative variables. It is appropriate in the same situations where multivariate regression would be. It determines orthogonal linear combinations of the variables (a set of canonical variates) within each set that best explain the variability both within and between sets. CCA allows us to summarize the relationships into fewer statistics while preserving the main facets of the relationships. In this way, the motivation for CCA is very similar to PCA as another dimension-reduction technique.

Canonical Correlation is an extension of the correlation of two univariate variables (x, y) to the relationship between two multivariate variables (X, Y).

Applications:

Psychological (3 variables) and Academic Variables (4 variables): A researcher has data on three psychological variables, four academic variables. The researcher seeks to indetify how the psychological variables correlate with academic performance, by the canonical variables to capture the association between the two sets of variables.

Objectives:

  1. Conducting CCA using R or a suitable tool.

  2. Determining the optimal number of canonical variate pairs to consider.

  3. Interpreting the scores of canonical variates.

  4. Interpret the relationships between variables across the two sets.

The objective of CCA is to find vectors $a$ and $b$ such that the correlation between $Xa$ and $Yb$ is maximized. $$Maximize: cor(Xa, Yb)$$

Subject to: $$ var(Xa) = 1, var(Yb) = 1 $$

More specifically: it finds linear combinations of the data, (a set of linear combinations) named U and V. U corresponds to the linear combinations from the first set of variables, X, and V corresponds to the second set of variables, Y. Each member of U is paired with a member of V.

\begin{align} U_1 & = a_{11}X_1 + a_{12}X_2 + \dots + a_{1p}X_p \\ U_2 & = a_{21}X_1 + a_{22}X_2 + \dots + a_{2p}X_p \\ & \vdots \\ U_p & = a_{p1}X_1 +a_{p2}X_2 + \dots +a_{pp}X_p\\ & \\ V_1 & = b_{11}Y_1 + b_{12}Y_2 + \dots + b_{1q}Y_q \\ V_2 & = b_{21}Y_1 + b_{22}Y_2 + \dots +b_{2q}Y_q \\ & \vdots \\ V_p & = b_{p1}Y_1 +b_{p2}Y_2 + \dots +b_{pq}Y_q\end{align}

First canonical variate pair: $\left( U _ { 1 } , V _ { 1 } \right)$ with the coefficients $a_{11}, a_{12}, \dots, a_{1p}$ and $b_{11}, b_{12}, \dots, b_{1q}$ being selected to maximize the canonical correlation of the first canonical variate pair, under the constraint that variances of the two canonical variates in that pair are equal to one $$\text{var}(U_1) = \text{var}(V_1) = 1$$.

R for canoncial correlation analysis

Chapter 11 Multidimensional Scaling¶

Introduction¶

Multidimensional Scaling (MDS) is a technique used to reduce the dimensionality of data while preserving the pairwise distances between observations. It is commonly used in fields like psychology, sociology, and marketing research to create visual representations of complex data sets.

Objectives of MDS¶

The main objective of MDS is to find a low-dimensional representation of a high-dimensional data set that preserves the pairwise distances as accurately as possible. This is achieved by minimizing a stress function, which measures the difference between the original and low-dimensional pairwise distances.

Given a dissimilarity matrix $ D = ( d_{ij} )_{p \times p} $, the aim is to find $ x_1, \ldots, x_n \in \mathbb{R}^k $ such that:

$$ \underbrace{d_{ij}^2}_{\text{raw distance}} \approx \underbrace{\|x_i - x_j\|^2}_{\text{new configuration}} $$

The goal is to identify a configurationtypically in a lower-dimensional space like $ \mathbb{R}^2 $ that preserves the Euclidean distances as closely as possible to the original dissimilarities or similarities.

Classical MDS: When the original distances are Euclidean, classical multidimensional scaling is used to find a configuration such that the configured distances are approximately equal to the original Euclidean distances. It focuses on global similarities , which are different with many manifold learning algorithms, which emphasize preserving local neighborhood relationships. MDS has limitations in producing non-linear embeddings. The original distances in $ D $ do not have to be Euclidean. They can represent any pairwise dissimilarities, even for qualitative comparisons between various objects. The algorithm is adapted based on whether the original distances are Euclidean (classical MDS) or non-Euclidean, or when dealing with qualitative similarities (general metric or non-metric MDS).

metric MDS:

Non-metric MDS differs by focusing on the rank-order relationships rather than the exact distances between items. It aims to find a monotonic relationship between the dissimilarities (or distances) in the original data and the Euclidean distances in the lower-dimensional space. This means that non-metric MDS does not preserve the exact numerical distances, but instead captures the general ordering of dissimilarities. It is a technique used to reduce complex, multidimensional data into a a lower (two-dimensional) representation or ordination. In the plot, points that are closer together indicate greater similarity between the corresponding samples.

#Find the distance matrix 
dMat = dist(iris[,-5]) # euclidean distances between the rows
fit = cmdscale(dMat,eig=TRUE, k=2) # k is the number of dim
#fit # view results

# plot solution
x = fit$points[,1]
y = fit$points[,2]

plot(x, y, xlab="Coordinate 1", ylab="Coordinate 2",
  main="Metric MDS", type="n")
text(x, y, labels = row.names(iris), cex=.7)

# Plot the points and label them with

       pch = 21, bg = "blue")

     labels = substr(iris$Species, 1, 2), 
     pos = 3, cex = 0.8)

# Add the cluster information to the plot
